  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "lesson-1",
      "name": "Introduction to the Internet",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does the Internet connect billions of devices across the globe?**\n\nStudents are introduced to the ways in which physical components like routers, switches and servers work with physical and wireless connections in order to transmit data globally. Students use an AI chatbot to simulate what it is like for devices to send and receive data reliably over the Internet. Finally, students are introduced to a new widget: The Internet Simulator, which they will use throughout this unit to explore the inner workings of the Internet.",
        "preparation": "- Test out the Internet Simulator. If you open up the level on two different tabs, you can use it by yourself.\n- Print copies of the AI Networks Chat activity guide (one for each student).",
        "student_overview": "**How does the Internet connect billions of devices across the globe?**\n\nThe Internet is made up of many physical components—routers, switches, servers, and more—that work together to send information all over the world. Some connections are wired, and some are wireless; they all work to help data travel quickly and reliably.\n\nIn this lesson, you’ll chat with an AI to explore how devices send and receive data. Then, you’ll get to use the Internet Simulator, a tool that helps you see how the Internet really works!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-1",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-2",
      "name": "Sending Bits",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How are messages broken into bits and sent across networks?**\n\nThis lesson engages students in a hands-on simulation of network communication, where they act as network devices to explore how data is transmitted efficiently and accurately. Through two structured challenges, students construct and optimize networks using strings, transmit binary messages using hand signals and cards, and experience challenges like delays, congestion, and errors in transmission. The lesson concludes with a discussion on how real-world networks address these challenges using protocols like TCP to ensure reliable data transfer.",
        "preparation": "- Print and cut out binary message cards (ensure they are in the correct order)\n- Prepare strings for each group (refer to the group size chart for correct amounts)\n- Ensure students have scratch paper and pencils for recording bits\n- Review the Teaching Guide Handout to understand student roles and key takeaways",
        "student_overview": "**How are messages broken into bits and sent across networks?**\n\nIn this lesson, you act as network devices to explore how data is sent across a network. By building different network structures and transmitting binary messages, you experience challenges like delays, errors, and congestion, then discuss how real networks solve these problems using protocols like TCP."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-2",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-3",
      "name": "IP Addresses",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Why do devices on the Internet need addresses?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how IP addresses enable communication across networks by acting as unique identifiers for devices. They trace the flow of data through a network, identify issues caused by duplicate IP addresses, and examine how AI optimizes network traffic and reliability.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the IP Addressing and Visualizing activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**Why do devices on the Internet need addresses?**\n\nWhen you stream a video or visit a website, your device needs a way to send and receive information reliably. In this lesson, you have an opportunity to follow how data moves through a network, see what happens when two devices share an IP address, and discover ways in which AI can help keep the Internet running smoothly."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-3",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-4",
      "name": "Routers and Redundancy",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does data find its way across the Internet and how does redundancy improve reliability?**\n\nThis lesson engages students in hands-on exploration of how routers direct data and how redundancy ensures network reliability. Through using an Internet Simulator and diagramming network paths, students analyze router logs and participate in discussions that connect real-world detours to data transmission, deepening their understanding of network resilience.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Network Diagram Analysis activity guide (one for each student).",
        "student_overview": "**How does data find its way across the Internet and how does redundancy improve reliability?**\n\nToday, you'll use an Internet Simulator to see how data travels across different routers and how messages sometimes take alternate routes. You'll create a network diagram, analyze logs, and discuss why having extra, backup paths is important for keeping the Internet running smoothly—just like finding a detour when your usual road is blocked."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-4",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-5",
      "name": "Packets",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does data travel reliably to reach its destination on an unreliable network?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how data is divided into packets for transmission and the challenges of ensuring reliable delivery. Through an unplugged simulation and an interactive Internet Simulator activity, students experience real-world issues like packet loss and delays. They develop and refine protocols to improve reliability. The lesson concludes with a discussion on TCP and UDP in order to highlight the tradeoffs networks face between reliability and speed.",
        "preparation": "- Review the Packets Unplugged Teacher Guide and decide:\n    - how you will arrange students in the classroom\n    - how you will assign IP addresses and partners for each student\n- Print copies of the Packets and Protocols activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How does data travel reliably to reach its destination on an unreliable network?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will explore how data is divided into packets for transmission and the challenges of ensuring reliable delivery. Through an unplugged simulation and an interactive Internet Simulator activity, you will experience real-world issues like packet loss and delays. You will develop and refine protocols to improve reliability. The lesson concludes with a discussion on TCP and UDP to highlight the trade-offs networks face between reliability and speed."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-5",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-6",
      "name": "HTTP and DNS",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do websites find their way to your browser using DNS and HTTP?**\n\nThis lesson explores how DNS (Domain Name System) and HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) work together to connect devices across the Internet. Students engage in hands-on activities, including an IP address collection exercise, a DNS query simulation, and an HTTP request exploration, to understand how devices locate websites and retrieve web content. Through discussions, chatbot interactions, and network monitoring exercises, students analyze how DNS translates domain names into IP addresses and how HTTP requests enable seamless access to online resources.",
        "preparation": "- Check that all student devices can open Developer Tools > Network Tab for HTTP observation\n- Print and cut out IP Address Labels for the warm-up activity\n- Print IP Address Collection Activity Guide (one for each student)\n- Print DNS Hierarchy Handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How do websites find their way to your browser using DNS and HTTP?**\n\nThe Internet depends on DNS to translate website names into IP addresses and HTTP to request and load web pages. In this lesson, you interact with simulations and tools to explore how these protocols help devices communicate and deliver web content efficiently."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-6",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-7",
      "name": "The Internet's Hidden Barriers",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Who has access to the Internet and who is left behind?**\n\nThis lesson explores the hidden barriers to Internet access, focusing on the digital divide and net neutrality. Students analyze real-world data from Pew Research to identify disparities in Internet access and engage in a case study simulation where they interact with personas facing digital accessibility challenges. Through discussions, data interpretation, and chatbot interactions, students connect these issues to education, employment, and civic participation, considering solutions to promote equitable Internet access.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Internet Access IRL activity guide.",
        "student_overview": "**Who has access to the Internet and who is left behind?**\n\nThe Internet is not equally accessible to everyone. In this lesson, you explore why some people have better Internet access than others, how this affects daily life, and what can be done to make online access more fair and inclusive."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-7",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-8",
      "name": "Internet Access Advocacy Campaign Project",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-8",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-9",
      "name": "Network Security",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What vulnerabilities exist in networks, and what strategies can mitigate their impact?**\n\nIn this lesson, students take on the role of cybersecurity analysts to investigate real-world network security threats and identify effective defenses. Through an interactive simulation, they explore vulnerabilities such as phishing, weak passwords, default credentials, and social engineering. After investigating each vulnerability, students propose a mitigation strategy that can be applied in a real-world context.",
        "preparation": "- Preview Level 1 to familiarize yourself with the scenarios, decision points, and key takeaways",
        "student_overview": "**What vulnerabilities exist in networks, and what strategies can mitigate their impact?**\n\nIn this less, you step into the role of a cyber security analyst in order to investigate real-world network security threats and determine how to defend against them. Through an interactive simulation, you explore common security vulnerabilities—phishing, weak passwords, default credentials, and social engineering—and propose defensive strategies  to help protect against future attacks."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-9",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-10",
      "name": "Emerging Technologies",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What makes AI effective at enhancing network security, and how does it compare to traditional methods?**\n\nThis lesson explores how AI enhances cybersecurity by detecting and responding to threats in real time. Through a hands-on simulation and discussions, students analyze how AI compares to traditional security methods and consider the challenges of implementing AI-driven solutions. The lesson encourages students to think critically about AI’s benefits, limitations, and role in network security.",
        "preparation": "- Print and cut out Threat Detected! Cards (one set for each pair of students)\n- Print AI Threat Detection Notetaker Activity Guide (one for each pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**What makes AI effective at enhancing network security, and how does it compare to traditional methods?**\n\nAI is transforming cybersecurity by detecting threats faster than traditional methods. In this lesson, you investigate how AI-powered tools improve security, their challenges, and how they compare to human decision-making in threat detection."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-10",
        "lesson_group.key": "",
        "script.name": "nati-pilot-content-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-11",
      "name": "Network Security Risk Assessment Project",
      "absolute_position": 11,
