  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "4dee76c2-bf50-4347-8377-29e2c0b80504",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What components might be needed to connect two devices across the world?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should draw on their prior knowledge and ideas about technology to brainstorm potential tools or systems needed for global communication. The goal is to get them thinking about the overall infrastructure (e.g., \"a connection,\" \"a way to direct messages\") that enables communication between devices. Students might identify components such as a WiFi or a cell tour, or even a satellite as ones needed to connect two devices. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *router* and *switch*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *internet towers* and *servers*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How might these components (routers, switches, servers) work together to connect devices across the world?*\n- *What might happen if one of these components fails during communication?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students identify experiences with using networking components like routers to connect to the internet, and by extension, to other devices. They also likely make connections to at least one of those components failing and subsequently losing their connection. Making these connections, and introducing the names of the components, will create a shared vocabulary and understanding as the foundation for the lesson. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dee76c2-bf50-4347-8377-29e2c0b80504",
        "lesson_activity.key": "05976db8-6d9e-4adf-8615-78f68c81cc9f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28c8e3f0-e30b-4c3b-945a-8c3bfcf2e537",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the *AI Networks Chat* activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 1.\n- **Level 1:** Students interact with an AI Chatbot to complete their activity guide. \n- **Level 2:** Students complete a check for understanding.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "AI Networks Chat",
        "progression_name": "AI Networks Chat"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28c8e3f0-e30b-4c3b-945a-8c3bfcf2e537",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "22795042-75ab-4d92-9573-ff9cc74fa057",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students are interacting with the chatbot and completing their activity guides, ask them questions about the responses they are getting and checking for understanding. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage curiosity in students! If students get vague answers, or answers they don’t understand, have them rephrase their questions to get better results. "
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students’ answers in Level 2 can be used as a formative assessment of their understanding of the function of each network component.\n\nActivity guides can also be collected and used to formatively assess student understanding of network components. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "22795042-75ab-4d92-9573-ff9cc74fa057",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92f6a6b7-9c6c-4184-ac7f-0ae9213068c8",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92f6a6b7-9c6c-4184-ac7f-0ae9213068c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2de015d-cb01-4067-ba5d-44561cb79d0a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Prepare students to explore The Internet Simulator.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show students how to make a connection with their partner.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Explore the Internet Simulator",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Keep it quick! Give a ***brief*** demo using the next two slides, then let students explore on their own. Bring them back for a discussion after they have explored for a few minutes."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2de015d-cb01-4067-ba5d-44561cb79d0a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2bfaa669-f0cc-4e14-ba21-32b37b71f769",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2bfaa669-f0cc-4e14-ba21-32b37b71f769",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7258c1d6-6206-457f-acbf-2e519d108278",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When you connect, you’ll see a visual representation of the direct connection between you and your partner. You’ll also see some options for changing how data is represented in the My Device tab.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7258c1d6-6206-457f-acbf-2e519d108278",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66687984-58fa-4120-bb62-cbb4d7a19cfb",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show students the \"My Device\" tab and demonstrate how you can turn on or off the different representations of data (binary, decimal, ASCII).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the different sections of the Internet Simulator widget for sending messages and reviewing message logs. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to join their partners on Level 3 in order to explore the Internet Simulator tool.",
        "progression_name": "Internet Simulator"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66687984-58fa-4120-bb62-cbb4d7a19cfb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e618015e-71d8-4d24-b40d-d6546063c729",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are sending and receiving messages, and ask them to describe what they notice in the logs. Get students to start thinking about how the Internet Simulator compares to the real thing by asking questions such as, “What happens when you try to send a message?” or “How does the simulator compare to the real Internet?”",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Keep this exploration around five minutes long. Students have more chances to explore and interact in later lessons—this is just a first look!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e618015e-71d8-4d24-b40d-d6546063c729",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "278700ad-919b-48b0-b620-83803d640d9f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "278700ad-919b-48b0-b620-83803d640d9f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9c7464bf-2684-4ebf-9e6b-c776f52204ed",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is the Internet Simulator similar to the Internet? How is it different?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Encourage students to speak from their own experience of using the Internet. Students might suggest that it is similar to the Internet because they can send information to another person and it all comes back to zeroes and ones. They might suggest it is different from the Internet because it can only send text and it takes a couple seconds to send a text instead of instantly."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9c7464bf-2684-4ebf-9e6b-c776f52204ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "02ed652c-8e10-46f9-a693-0685c72d3b17",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "02ed652c-8e10-46f9-a693-0685c72d3b17",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d76f2de1-3774-4361-9cb3-fed0f8108e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d18a8908-9da2-4e44-8db9-2816fd101e0b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to briefly share their thoughts about how the Internet connects devices across the globe before individually writing their own response to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to go beyond basic definitions by making connections to today’s activities."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- The basic infrastructure of the Internet, including key components like routers, switches, servers, and physical / wireless connections\n- An example from the lesson such as how a request for a website travels from a user’s device to a server and back"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d18a8908-9da2-4e44-8db9-2816fd101e0b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ce36416b-55b5-4ade-b623-4ba88626a8c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c95c4c6b-b1a5-4c28-96a2-7f3193b8de97",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c95c4c6b-b1a5-4c28-96a2-7f3193b8de97",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ce36416b-55b5-4ade-b623-4ba88626a8c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6709f07b-ca7b-4ad3-bc9c-fcf709cbf12e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How does the Internet connect billions of devices across the globe?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that the Internet connects devices through a global network of routers, switches, and servers that direct and transmit data across wired and wireless connections. They should also recognize that data takes different forms (ASCII, decimal, binary).  "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6709f07b-ca7b-4ad3-bc9c-fcf709cbf12e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ce36416b-55b5-4ade-b623-4ba88626a8c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9d4a5cfa-cd8e-4f03-8709-c0eefd6025a5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"The Internet: Wires, Cables, & Wifi”. Encourage students to think about how computers convert data into signals as they watch the video.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The video will stop at 2:53. As students watch the video, encourage them to think about how computers convert data into signals. After watching the video, students should recognize that computers convert digital data into signals for transmission. Encourage students to think about the ways in which devices are able to communicate accurately, and the complexity of global communication."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9d4a5cfa-cd8e-4f03-8709-c0eefd6025a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4bd57ae-b77c-4b72-96a0-5dedd3788df3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eb4e3370-743b-4bca-a72e-894222dd9aa5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eb4e3370-743b-4bca-a72e-894222dd9aa5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4bd57ae-b77c-4b72-96a0-5dedd3788df3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b18c1ba-5c4a-4730-9b4f-09a76810b77c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why is binary such an effective way for computers to send and receive information?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students to recognize that binary aligns with physical states (simple on/off, light/dark) that are easy to detect reliably. Students may mention that binary transmission reduces complexity, minimizes errors, and can be universally adopted for data transmission.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to respond, ask guiding questions, such as \"What happens if a signal is weak or noisy? Why is binary better in these cases?\" or \"Can you think of other systems that use only two states (like light switches, Morse code)?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b18c1ba-5c4a-4730-9b4f-09a76810b77c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4bd57ae-b77c-4b72-96a0-5dedd3788df3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0b295e01-c9fd-485b-bb81-83a02ce73072",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0b295e01-c9fd-485b-bb81-83a02ce73072",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4bd57ae-b77c-4b72-96a0-5dedd3788df3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7dbe14aa-62f7-4d4a-a7a9-ec7ed1370bcb",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7dbe14aa-62f7-4d4a-a7a9-ec7ed1370bcb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e4bd57ae-b77c-4b72-96a0-5dedd3788df3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f645dbf9-7970-45af-bc39-ec8f26ba0198",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of 5-7.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group of students a set of data cards (to be set aside and used with Network Challenge 2) and string according to the following chart:\n- Groups of 5: 10 strings\n- Groups of 6: 15 strings\n- Groups of 7: 21 strings",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "String Calculation: The number of strings per group is determined by adding up all numbers less than the group size.\n\nExample:\n- Group of 5: Needs 4+3+2+1 = 10 strings\n- Group of 8: Needs 7+6+5+4+3+2+1 = 28 strings"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f645dbf9-7970-45af-bc39-ec8f26ba0198",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "752e8774-eeee-494f-8024-fc7be76556f9",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "752e8774-eeee-494f-8024-fc7be76556f9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2bcc3ea-179e-47ca-9986-0cdda72fd553",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the activity by explaining that students will act as network devices to simulate how bits (1s and 0s) are transmitted over a network. Emphasize that they must follow the instructions carefully to ensure accurate transmission.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Refer to the Teaching Guide - Human Network Bit Transmission Challenge handout to gain a complete understanding of how the Network and Transmission Challenges should work, how to set them up, and key takeaways. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2bcc3ea-179e-47ca-9986-0cdda72fd553",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2943c331-4949-4c7e-9f9a-28cc99bcf669",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2943c331-4949-4c7e-9f9a-28cc99bcf669",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "050990c0-323c-47bb-ac29-c8cc4102dd09",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that each string represents a direct connection between two devices. Each student can have multiple connections but can only be directly linked to another person through one string at a time.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students create a fully connected network by linking every person to every other person with strings.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure each student has direct connections to everyone else in the group. Look for students noticing inefficiencies and encourage them to share observations.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allow students to talk and work together to discover what their fully connected network should look like. Provide guidance to any groups who are struggling. See the Teaching Guide - Human Network Bit Transmission Challenge handout for an example of what this should look like.  "
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Observe if students recognize that having direct connections to everyone is inefficient. Listen for discussions about how difficult it would be to scale this model to a large network."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "050990c0-323c-47bb-ac29-c8cc4102dd09",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24688766-7c28-4439-b4e8-3a20cfc6c9ea",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24688766-7c28-4439-b4e8-3a20cfc6c9ea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0ddcb13-7300-42c9-8b6f-d3ef84a85803",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Once groups have their fully connected network, instruct them to assign roles. Explain what each role involves and provide the Sender with the Transmission Challenge 1 card so they know what bits they need to send. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use the metronome on the slide to keep transmission time consistent, transmitting one bit by holding up a 1 or 0 every second. If students miss a bit or get confused, don’t correct them right away—this will help highlight the need for protocols like TCP later."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0ddcb13-7300-42c9-8b6f-d3ef84a85803",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "16673e0e-4fbb-4e3a-a444-0ab8164b0452",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "16673e0e-4fbb-4e3a-a444-0ab8164b0452",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9d0ac15-6ce3-47f4-8482-1956d72b1da2",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have the sender transmit a full message (HEY) using binary while the receiver writes it down.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage Network Monitors to be actively engaged—they should note if a bit is dropped, arrives late, or is recorded incorrectly. Observe whether students fall behind or misinterpret bits. If errors occur, discuss why protocols are needed to correct mistakes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have groups translate their binary message to ASCII using the table.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for groups who get the wrong translation and ask them where the error occurred in transmission.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students notice errors in their message, have them reflect: How could an automated system detect and correct errors? This sets up the need for protocols like TCP."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9d0ac15-6ce3-47f4-8482-1956d72b1da2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2441c5b-8005-4702-bcc3-5b04945550af",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2441c5b-8005-4702-bcc3-5b04945550af",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d7420042-c06e-42ad-847c-7017a1064a18",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What did you notice about this fully connected network?*\n- *Would it be realistic for the Internet to work this way?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize:\n- **Advantage:** Transmission was **quick** and **direct** since every device was connected.\n- **Disadvantages:**\n   - **Not scalable**—too many direct connections make large networks impractical.\n   - **Still prone to errors**—even with direct paths, mistakes in transmission can still occur.\n   - **Real networks don’t work like this**—instead of every device connecting directly, **the Internet relies on routers and paths to relay messages efficiently**.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that in this second challenge, the same rules apply: each string represents a direct connection between two devices. Each student can have multiple connections but can only be directly linked to another person through one string at a time.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that in this second challenge, students must remove unnecessary connections while still ensuring that everyone can communicate indirectly. Have students reduce their connections, ensuring that even if one string is cut, all students can still communicate.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for groups struggling to maintain connectivity. Ask: If you remove too many connections, will everyone still receive data?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that this reflects how real networks work—we don’t connect every device directly; instead, we rely on routers and pathways. Encourage students to strategically place their connections."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d7420042-c06e-42ad-847c-7017a1064a18",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0a278d2c-b176-4760-afad-e6ae1ef5ebac",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0a278d2c-b176-4760-afad-e6ae1ef5ebac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70a02e66-05b4-4f1f-a7f7-ab7fa3e35f33",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Once groups have their more efficient network, instruct them to assign roles. Explain what each role involves and provide the Sender with the Transmission Challenge 2 cards that need to be sent to the Receiver. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use the metronome on the slide to keep transmission time consistent, transmitting one card every second. Remind students to only hold one card at a time, however, it is okay to allow students (routers) to hold too many bits as this creates network congestion and is fin for students to experience this firsthand. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70a02e66-05b4-4f1f-a7f7-ab7fa3e35f33",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f4f9df5-5105-4fda-9a0f-f19a2bbb9252",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f4f9df5-5105-4fda-9a0f-f19a2bbb9252",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "33327270-7f37-4f3e-b0e2-29ba883ab441",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to send the binary message through the network using the \"not busy\" rule for routers. Ensure each bit card is passed at a rate of one per second using the metronome for pacing.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Observe if routers get backed up (this mimics real-world Internet congestion) so that you can discuss this during the activity discussion debrief.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have groups check if they successfully transmitted the message by translating the binary to ASCII using the table.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for groups who get the wrong translation and encourage them to reflect on where the error occurred in transmission.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If errors occur, have students identify where the transmission failed—did a router delay a bit? Did packets arrive out of order? Relate this to real-world network errors—like when a video buffers or an image loads slowly on a website."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "33327270-7f37-4f3e-b0e2-29ba883ab441",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b163a99f-0fbd-42bf-821e-ad005aec801f",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b163a99f-0fbd-42bf-821e-ad005aec801f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28bec49f-05b7-433c-bf74-fc6197797067",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.\n- *How does the network setup compare to the real Internet?*\n- *What delays occurred? How does this reflect real-world networks?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand:\n- Real networks face delays, congestion, and packet loss.\n- Messages may arrive out of order, requiring reassembly (similar to how TCP works).\n- More efficient networks still experience bottlenecks.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is one way we might check if some bits were missing or not received in the right order?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify error-checking methods (like sequence numbers), resending messing data if a bit is lost, or confirming receipt before moving on (acknowledgements in networking). ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to suggest solutions, prompt them to think about how online services fix errors (e.g., file downloads that resume from where they left off)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28bec49f-05b7-433c-bf74-fc6197797067",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5728e67d-9ec5-4e65-b0ce-d6fd14c2f66d",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5728e67d-9ec5-4e65-b0ce-d6fd14c2f66d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24d9a1d4-76dd-4cd7-ab6d-bb97eb716305",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Transmission Control Protocol (TCP)*. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It’s okay to briefly introduce TCP here, but there’s no need to go into full detail. In an upcoming lesson, students will create their own TCP-like protocol using the Internet Simulator, where they will develop a deeper understanding of how TCP ensures reliable data transmission. This introduction should simply help them recognize that there are rules in place to correct errors and organize data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24d9a1d4-76dd-4cd7-ab6d-bb97eb716305",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "045b3c9c-7b25-4e4f-8d8a-9f927a873865",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "045b3c9c-7b25-4e4f-8d8a-9f927a873865",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b78a84ed-7b32-46c9-89ee-737e97ac7192",
      "position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the second half of the video \"The Internet: Wire, Cables, & WiFi\" .\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why might we use one transmission method over another in different situations?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that different transmission methods (electricity, light, and radio waves) have trade-offs in speed, range, and reliability. The internet choose transmission methods based on the situation (e.g., WiFi for mobility, fiber optics for speed)."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b78a84ed-7b32-46c9-89ee-737e97ac7192",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66f95018-9554-4d79-8a7b-f3c976350519",
      "position": 22,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66f95018-9554-4d79-8a7b-f3c976350519",
        "lesson_activity.key": "58b697ee-0333-4fd8-abb3-50d3f2c7a621"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c2cdecc4-2ccd-43c3-97c1-97fa3cd2c86f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to briefly share their thoughts about how messages are broken into bits and sent across networks before individually writing their own response to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to build on each other’s ideas instead of just repeating the same answer. When writing their individual responses in the Unit Guide, students should include at least one specific example from today’s activity."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- how binary data is transmitted across a network.\n- how network structure and protocols improve the reliability of data transmission."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c2cdecc4-2ccd-43c3-97c1-97fa3cd2c86f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e0201c42-f401-4730-8b0c-ac8998a0ccee"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b8c69ac5-8a1c-4bad-9288-fc185bd7de50",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *Imagine you were in a room with 5 other people, all with the same name as you. What might happen when you start communicating?*\n- *How could you solve these problems?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students recognize the challenges of communication without unique identifiers. They may share examples like: \n- Struggling to get the right person’s attention\n- Multiple people responding at once\n- Needing a system to avoid mixups\n\nThis discussion sets the groundwork for the connection to devices needing unique addresses to communicate over the Internet.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** After the discussion, explain that just like names can cause confusion, devices need unique IP addresses to communicate clearly.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b8c69ac5-8a1c-4bad-9288-fc185bd7de50",
        "lesson_activity.key": "222bb803-3ffa-4325-8e50-592e16ef75a2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a67a4fda-1abe-4c02-8e33-b2714112c94e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the IP Addressing and Visualizing Networks activity guide. Ensure that each pair has access to at least three different colored pens (or pencils, highlighters, etc.) for visualizing AI driven solutions in later scenarios. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to assign the correct IP addresses to the devices on the Network Diagram of their handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are correctly labeling devices based on the routing table. Watch for students mistakenly assigning the same IP to multiple devices or skipping octets.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click on the animated slide to display the prompts:\n- *Why do devices on a network need unique IP addresses?*\n- *What might happen if two devices had the same IP address? How could this impact communication?*\n- *How does the router know where to send data packets when multiple devices are connected to it?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand why unique IP addresses are essential for clear and reliable communication within a network. Guide students to draw parallels to real-world addressing systems (e.g., postal addresses, phone numbers) and discuss how unique identifiers prevent confusion. Encourage them to consider the consequences of duplicate IP addresses, such as misdirected or lost data, similar to multiple people sharing the same phone number. Additionally, students should connect this concept to the routing table, recognizing how routers use IP addresses to efficiently direct network traffic. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *IP address*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 4 to illustrate the flow of information in each level’s scenario on their network diagrams by connecting devices, drawing arrows, and using colors for AI solutions.\n- **Level 1:** Students illustrate the flow of information in a local network scenario.\n- **Level 2:** Students illustrate the flow of information in a scenario with a local network that is connected to an ISP.**\nLevel 3:\n- **Level 3:** Students illustrate the flow of information in a scenario involving requesting and receiving data from a website server.\n- **Level 4:** Students illustrate the flow of information in three scenarios involving AI-based solutions for network efficiency.",
        "name": "IP Addressing and Visualizing Networks",
        "progression_name": "IP Addressing and Visualizing"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a67a4fda-1abe-4c02-8e33-b2714112c94e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d21d9bc-e673-443a-9228-6e55228e6b47"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86aeef43-6a9f-4187-b12e-fccb3b25f644",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students explore the scenarios, encourage them to actively interact with the network diagram handout by drawing arrows. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This activity can serve as an informal formative assessment as the teacher circulates and listens to student discussions. Listen for students explaining routing and IP addressing correctly, check that students are correctly applying lines, labels, and colors, and ask a few students to walk through their network diagrams to ensure they understand the flow of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86aeef43-6a9f-4187-b12e-fccb3b25f644",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d21d9bc-e673-443a-9228-6e55228e6b47"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29642c2f-abd5-4248-9c2f-d0fa65a4a97c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29642c2f-abd5-4248-9c2f-d0fa65a4a97c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d21d9bc-e673-443a-9228-6e55228e6b47"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66b2938d-be51-4c3f-857c-17ff355d59aa",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click on the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How do IP addresses enable communication between devices on different networks, even across the globe?*\n- *What are some advantages of using AI to assist with routing compared to traditional methods?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that IP addresses allow devices to communicate globally by providing unique identifiers that routers use to forward data. Encourage them to connect these identifiers to real-world identifiers they are already familiar with like address numbers on homes. Students also are able to explain ways in which AI can improve routing efficiency, such as detected congestion, resolving IP conflicts, and adjusting traffic in real time. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66b2938d-be51-4c3f-857c-17ff355d59aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d21d9bc-e673-443a-9228-6e55228e6b47"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17ecc762-6907-4f99-a281-40af9a483e06",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17ecc762-6907-4f99-a281-40af9a483e06",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d21d9bc-e673-443a-9228-6e55228e6b47"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a643da34-4714-4084-8a77-2ba6a1adf5ca",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"The Internet: IP Addresses & DNS\" (0:00–3:23).",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a643da34-4714-4084-8a77-2ba6a1adf5ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d4df1b3b-1253-462f-9c1f-0b7277e24457"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f6ab6e4-7528-4214-b191-237fbe79ae65",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f6ab6e4-7528-4214-b191-237fbe79ae65",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d4df1b3b-1253-462f-9c1f-0b7277e24457"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e1663f75-e179-4860-913d-60e691aeacb8",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to briefly share their thoughts why devices on the Internet need addresses before individually writing their own response to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to go beyond basic definitions by making connections to today’s activities."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- Why unique IP addresses are necessary for devices to communicate reliably\n- How routers use IP addresses to direct traffic (at a high level)\n- An example from the lesson, such as how AI improves network efficiency"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e1663f75-e179-4860-913d-60e691aeacb8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d4df1b3b-1253-462f-9c1f-0b7277e24457"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bf656100-3e07-4b81-9257-9e78b64f0109",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What happens when a road is closed? How do cars still reach their destination?*\n- *What would happen if there were no other roads available?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that detours keep traffic moving even when there’s an issue (redundancy ensures reliability). Without alternative routes, traffic (or data) cannot reach its destination (no redundancy = failure). Guide students to understand that, just like roads, the Internet has many paths for data to travel. If one path is closed or busy, data can take a detour. This redundancy ensures the Internet remains reliable, even during failures or high traffic.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Avoid explicitly mentioning the Internet during the warm-up. Let students connect the analogy to networks as the lesson progresses. The warm-up primes them to understand redundancy by introducing it conceptually without explicitly framing it in technical terms.\n\nIf time allows, extend the discussion by asking students for other examples: \"What are some other systems where backups or alternatives are important? For example, what happens if your phone dies—how do you stay in touch?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bf656100-3e07-4b81-9257-9e78b64f0109",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a10e9b9c-71f3-4fa0-a10a-95318f72405e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d380aec7-8e56-4150-807a-a67e519df872",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d380aec7-8e56-4150-807a-a67e519df872",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a10e9b9c-71f3-4fa0-a10a-95318f72405e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71f5c8d7-ddf0-487e-9095-2a5fb646bbac",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71f5c8d7-ddf0-487e-9095-2a5fb646bbac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a10e9b9c-71f3-4fa0-a10a-95318f72405e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39486bb4-2029-4d09-9289-88b48a786503",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:**  Provide each student with a copy of *Network Diagram Analysis* activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Internet Simulator and how students should join. They can choose any of the the routers as long as it's not the same as their partner's.",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Internet Simulator and Networks Diagram Analysis",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Add up to as many routers as there are students in your classroom. This will help illustrate how many hops across multiple routers their messages take. \n\nYou can also assign multiple students to a single router, just make sure that elbow partners are on different routers. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39486bb4-2029-4d09-9289-88b48a786503",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0639870-57e0-4c09-bca6-e88b1af250d2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0639870-57e0-4c09-bca6-e88b1af250d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7c796db7-dfcb-4d57-8c69-118646892297",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students need to know the IP address to send their partner a message.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain how to send a message to their partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain how to navigate to the \"Log Browser\" from the \"Router\" tab to access the message data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to read the logs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7c796db7-dfcb-4d57-8c69-118646892297",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d361dd4f-0c60-4fde-a229-94f3da7c04c2",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "First, choose the \"show traffic to me\" option in the first dropdown menu and \"show all routers\" in the second dropdown menu. The path that these messages take are what you will be diagramming. If we look at this message that asks \"What’s your favorite color?\", we see that the message starts at Router 1 because this person has an id of router 1.1, then it goes to router 8, 6, and finally Router 2. This person’s partner is at Router 2.12, so the message got to them. If you’re unsure which router was pinged first, look at the timestamp in the first column. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d361dd4f-0c60-4fde-a229-94f3da7c04c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1b8f61d-78b2-4a9f-aadd-5ebe8a396d3d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students should diagram the path their message took on their activity guide for up to three messages.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate adding the nodes and IP addresses of their device and their partner's device."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1b8f61d-78b2-4a9f-aadd-5ebe8a396d3d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bc0c972d-c239-41fc-a51a-a00bf785fdb7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A node represents any device that connects to a network—this could be a phone, computer, printer, router, or even a smart thermostat. Routers play a crucial role in networking because they connect multiple devices (or nodes) to the Internet and help direct data between them. While routers themselves are also considered nodes, their primary function is to manage network traffic and assign local IP addresses to devices within a network.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bc0c972d-c239-41fc-a51a-a00bf785fdb7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "15655903-1889-42e2-a48a-e03a9cec0aa8",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 and 2.\n- **Level 1:** Students use the Internet Simulator to diagram messages sent through the network. \n- **Level 2:** Students complete a check for understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Internet Simulator and Networks Diagram Analysis"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "15655903-1889-42e2-a48a-e03a9cec0aa8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1cb759c-705c-4394-b1f3-c43e1620f5f9",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they send messages. While they will diagram all messages sent over the network, ensure they only send messages to their partner. Check that they use the router logs correctly to follow the path each message took and ensure their diagrams accurately represent those paths. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let students know that it is okay if they don’t have time to diagram every single message, especially if you have a large number of messages. The goal is for them to diagram enough messages to see that they are not taking direct paths to their destinations, but rather bouncing through multiple routers, and the paths messages are taking will most likely not be the same exact path each time.  "
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The activity guide can be used as a formative assessment of student understanding of routers and the idea of data taking different paths (redundancy)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1cb759c-705c-4394-b1f3-c43e1620f5f9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c09c6a39-3c35-4c8e-bf61-20bc7dcdee6a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c09c6a39-3c35-4c8e-bf61-20bc7dcdee6a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "497e24a6-cb9d-4a64-bed6-6ee2c5cbad08",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How did the redundancy in your network help prevent complete failure?*\n- *What might have happened if no redundant paths were available?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students explain how redundancy in a network helps maintain connectivity by providing alternative paths when a connection fails. They describe specific examples of how redundant paths allow data to continue flowing, such as rerouting traffic through different nodes or links. Additionally, students discuss the potential consequences of having no redundancy, including total network failure, loss of communication, or disruptions in internet access.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *Why do you think routers chose new paths for some messages?*\n- *How might redundant paths be important during high-traffic events, like streaming live sports or during natural disasters?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for and guide students to the following points:\nRouters often choose new paths for messages to avoid problems like traffic jams or broken connections. If one path is too busy or isn’t working well, the router can send the message along a different route so it still reaches its destination quickly and reliably. This process is similar to taking a detour on the way to school when your usual road is closed or too congested.\nRedundant paths are like backup routes on a map. During high-traffic events, such as live sports streaming when many people are online, or during natural disasters when some parts of the network might be damaged, these extra routes help keep the network working smoothly. If one path gets overloaded or fails, data can still travel through another route, ensuring that information gets to its destination without interruption.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Closing"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "497e24a6-cb9d-4a64-bed6-6ee2c5cbad08",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96ba1d34-8626-4016-9fd3-b2c37ac39b7e",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96ba1d34-8626-4016-9fd3-b2c37ac39b7e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5f9e655-62fd-4e07-9cc4-db72717adfb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "246cd4e4-f9aa-4552-adb7-ef72f007de25",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write down idea for how data finds its way across the internet and one idea for how redundancy improves reliability. Instruct students to jot their ideas down in bullet points rather than complete sentences to allow time for them to share their ideas with a Give One, Get One protocol. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the Give One, Get One activity and direct students to participate in a Give One, Get One to share their ideas to the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity. Click the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue.\n\nGive One, Get One encourages students to seek and share ideas and information. Students circulate the classroom and pair up with a partner when prompted by the teacher. Each student \"gives\" or shares one of their ideas as the other student \"gets\" or listens and writes it down. The teacher then prompts students to find new partners and repeat the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "246cd4e4-f9aa-4552-adb7-ef72f007de25",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b98946cd-5f30-4f4e-a303-b7f817d8687f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f46c921-6fc5-4e97-bb78-e0e4fc5009b4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts. \n- *Imagine you’re sending a big package, but have to break it into smaller boxes. What challenges might you face in getting everything delivered safely?*\n- *What might happen to some of the boxes along the way?*\n- *What could make sure they all arrive?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion sets the stage for the challenges students will encounter in the unplugged activity. Encourage students to consider challenges like packages getting lost or delayed, arriving out of order, as well as ways to improve reliability, such as labeling and tracking. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Do not explicitly mention labeling, lost boxes, or reconstructing the message. Let students arrive at these challenges naturally during the unplugged activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f46c921-6fc5-4e97-bb78-e0e4fc5009b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7898c3a7-fe92-485e-9b19-ad7322c3a430"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d92af2f8-917b-4f9a-b818-831d8580890f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d92af2f8-917b-4f9a-b818-831d8580890f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7898c3a7-fe92-485e-9b19-ad7322c3a430"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7432553c-450c-4796-a969-c5034a14b946",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7432553c-450c-4796-a969-c5034a14b946",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7898c3a7-fe92-485e-9b19-ad7322c3a430"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96f2e4df-2741-4747-9f72-6e6827ae5f5f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a piece of scratch paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to make a simple drawing, or write a handwritten message on their scratch piece of paper."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96f2e4df-2741-4747-9f72-6e6827ae5f5f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e651a30d-458c-428b-ae7a-2d085f7cafba",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have just made a message that you are going to send to someone else on the other side of the room. However, we’re going to imagine that it’s too big to send all at once.  So tear it into four pieces.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e651a30d-458c-428b-ae7a-2d085f7cafba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7b739f0b-c992-4547-aa9d-1fe8a9207e29",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Assign each student an IP address and a partner. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Depending on the context of each classroom, assigning partners and IP addresses may look different. Some possible implementations are below: \n- Project a seating chart with pre-assigned IP addresses\n- Count students in real time to assign IP addresses\n- Provide general guidelines for IP addresses and allow students to choose their own (e.g. \"It must be two numbers between 1-100, separated by a period.\") "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7b739f0b-c992-4547-aa9d-1fe8a9207e29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63fcfed6-d0c8-4f12-9129-550f831356f1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63fcfed6-d0c8-4f12-9129-550f831356f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "12e78d1a-05d1-4bb6-ba95-3c59b0619221",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask students to look across the room to find a partner - they can point at or make eye contact with someone.  (Students in the middle should find partners who aren’t at the middle table). Once each student has a partner, ask students to tell their partner their IP address.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to address each of their pieces. Students should write their partner’s IP address on each piece of paper that makes up their drawing, clearly indicating that it is going to that address. For example - \"To: 4.2\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the rules to the students, and check that all students understand what they need to do.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Call \"Go!\" to begin the activity! ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There will probably be enough \"traffic\" going around for issues of delayed packets and dropped packets to emerge. But if you want to force the issue you can try a few of the following:\n- As students are passing paper, teacher can participate or try to interfere by delaying and occasionally destroying pieces of paper.\n- You may also prepare a different drawing to send to one student, just to introduce some confusion."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "12e78d1a-05d1-4bb6-ba95-3c59b0619221",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6bbc1ff0-c00d-4508-a29e-56da00cae286",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bbc1ff0-c00d-4508-a29e-56da00cae286",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c2d07f2b-cdb6-4b16-b915-c60a380fe604",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Call \"Stop!\" after about five minutes, or at least one student was able to receive and reconstruct the image. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts. \n- *What challenges did you experience in passing your packets?*\n- *What happened if packets didn’t arrive or were delayed?*\n- *How could we address these issues in a protocol?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students discuss a variety of challenges in transmission (lost or delayed packets, etc) and reassembly. Without necessarily defining specific protocols, encourage students to recognize that rules are needed to ensure packets arrive accurately and in order. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Try using the Pairs and Squares protocol to facilitate this discussion. Students discuss each prompt with their partner, and then share with a group of four. The teacher calls on one or two groups and asks for a representative to summarize their discussion."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c2d07f2b-cdb6-4b16-b915-c60a380fe604",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b37c16a9-919e-4344-8904-a6c488eede98",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b37c16a9-919e-4344-8904-a6c488eede98",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1d7ba44-412d-4249-b381-7eeb3dc7eb8f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 1. Students explore the changes to the Internet Simulator by sending messages to their partner at a different router. ",
        "progression_name": "Internet Simulator: Packets"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1d7ba44-412d-4249-b381-7eeb3dc7eb8f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03a46c9d-be57-40b3-a16e-4380dfee1f24",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students explore encourage them to point out the ways in which the simulator has changed. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use a two or three-minute timer to keep exploration focused and to ensure students have time to for the next part of the activity. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03a46c9d-be57-40b3-a16e-4380dfee1f24",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b15a1260-acc3-4642-b375-2c22bcaa6a11",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b15a1260-acc3-4642-b375-2c22bcaa6a11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8cb84ed7-69e1-4c5b-bcc4-2348b4b5dc45",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts. \n- *What did you notice about the Internet Simulator in this level?*\n- *What do you wonder about the Internet Simulator in this level?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students mention new features like packets being limited to 80 bits and a new \"Add Packet\" button for splitting messages into multiple packets. Encourage students to explore how whether or not they received all of the packets they were expecting, and if they were in the proper order. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Highlight the new features of the Internet Simulator: \n- Packets are limited to 80 bits (64 bits for data, 16 bits for metadata).\n- A message can be split into multiple packets using the \"Add Packet\" button.\n- Packets may arrive out of order or get dropped during transmission.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Packets and Protocols activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to draft a protocol to address packet challenges they experienced during the unplugged activity (e.g., numbering packets, confirming receipt, requesting missing packets).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to test their protocols on Level 1.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Circulate, observe, and ask guiding questions such as \"What happens if your confirmation message gets dropped?\" or \"How will you handle packets arriving out of order?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- **Emphasize Iteration and Learning**: \"It’s okay if your protocol isn’t completely perfect! The goal of this activity isn’t to design a flawless protocol but to discover the challenges involved in ensuring reliable data transmission. Focus on exploring what issues your protocol needs to address and how it can handle those challenges.\"\n- **Encourage Flexibility**: \"If your first protocol doesn’t work as expected, that’s fine—use it as an opportunity to test and refine your ideas. This mirrors real-world protocol development, which often involves multiple iterations.\"\n- **Reinforce the Key Takeaway**: \"The point of this activity is to realize how complex it is to design a protocol that accounts for dropped, delayed, or out-of-order packets. Even if your protocol isn’t perfect, you’re learning to think like a network engineer!\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8cb84ed7-69e1-4c5b-bcc4-2348b4b5dc45",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc1c4c4a-9688-475b-af3c-0c0f37357c6e",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc1c4c4a-9688-475b-af3c-0c0f37357c6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dabdb7ac-a19c-462f-af78-ef090cd46ccb",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to write a second draft to address problems they encountered.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to test their revised protocol on Level 1 and complete the Check for Understanding on Level 2. ",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Teachers can display anonymous student responses and go over misconceptions or ask students what similarities and differences they notice about the responses"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The check for understanding question can be used to formatively assess student understanding of how data packets are reassembled after transmission.  "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dabdb7ac-a19c-462f-af78-ef090cd46ccb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1d10e345-c86f-477a-8c12-e96a825b5cc2",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1d10e345-c86f-477a-8c12-e96a825b5cc2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "02301233-4913-4803-98cd-5255137da113",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the TCP protocol they learned about in a previous lesson. Guide students to make the connection that they they just created a TCP protocol with their partner. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the UDP protocol to students.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"The Internet: Packets, Routing, and Reliability\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What would simulating UDP in the Internet Simulator look like?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students mention that UPD is focused on speed, so simulating it on the Internet simulator would involve sending packets without checking for errors or missing data. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "02301233-4913-4803-98cd-5255137da113",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a52ca956-f95f-44a4-b893-d7d908e25e11",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a52ca956-f95f-44a4-b893-d7d908e25e11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9ba2a1f-7384-4306-b564-95cb79888207"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7746349b-e6c8-4a3b-af79-b1434f8b2f5f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of 3-4.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This: **Direct students to briefly share their thoughts on how data travels reliably despite an unreliable network before writing their own response to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to build on each other’s ideas instead of just repeating the same answer. When writing their individual responses in the Unit Guide, students should include at least one specific example from today’s activity."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- How network protocols (e.g., TCP) ensure reliable data transmission despite dropped, delayed, or out-of-order packets.\n- The role of packet numbering, acknowledgments, and retransmission in ensuring messages are reassembled correctly at their destination."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7746349b-e6c8-4a3b-af79-b1434f8b2f5f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "af790b59-1eec-48e0-8ddf-f429800e8a78"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2637c8d6-536d-4d7e-bfbe-35f030afd411",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** As students enter class hand each of them a single IP address. Also give each student a copy of the IP Address Collection activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain to the students that today we're going to finish our study of the layers of the Internet and learn about two final protocols and we’re going to just hop right in! Inform students that when they walked into the room you handed each student a slip of paper - this is their IP address. Remind students that we know that in order to communicate on the internet you need to know the IP address of the other computer and that so far we've let you ask one another's addresses when communicating on the Internet Simulator, but this can be tricky.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students’ goal is to create a list of every one of your classmates IP addresses. The only rules:\n- They may walk around the room\n- They may share information with classmates\n- They may talk and share information with only ONE classmate at a time\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students are working, circulate quietly through the room and do the following:\n- Approach a student and silently take their IP address slip away from them.\n- Give that person a new IP address slip (or a re-used IP address).\n- Repeat the above two steps as many times as you can, as you circulate the room.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This quick unplugged activity helps students understand why the DNS exists in the first place. With devices joining the internet all the time it's impossible for each device to keep track of each other device's IP address.\n\nThis activity can be done very quickly, typically in about 3 minutes, before students start to see the core challenge. If students start running away from you that's a good sign they've seen what makes this activity tricky!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2637c8d6-536d-4d7e-bfbe-35f030afd411",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c804b45a-de0d-4348-b799-24de1183c27f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37f4ea28-33cb-49b6-bbdb-8051ef2b5704",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37f4ea28-33cb-49b6-bbdb-8051ef2b5704",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c804b45a-de0d-4348-b799-24de1183c27f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a471171-0fa0-48e9-a3bf-c3ce74cbf3e9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a471171-0fa0-48e9-a3bf-c3ce74cbf3e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c804b45a-de0d-4348-b799-24de1183c27f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cd3377b3-ba4b-4a7f-b6b7-20c29454c7c6",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.\n- *Why do you think I was switching IP addresses?*\n- *If IP addresses can change, is there a better way for everyone to know everyone else’s IP address?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The main takeaways from the discussion are:\n- Devices are joining and leaving the Internet all the time. IP addresses don't stay constant. If you go to a coffee shop or restart your browser your device might be assigned a new IP address.\n- If IP addresses are switching, it's very hard for each computer to keep an accurate list.\n- It would make more sense if there were one system that kept track of all that information\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce DNS to students.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cd3377b3-ba4b-4a7f-b6b7-20c29454c7c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c804b45a-de0d-4348-b799-24de1183c27f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a18ddc93-c0d3-4841-a1dd-35e2e4d285c7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the goal and rules for the Internet Simulator DNS task and answer any questions they may have before transitioning to the computer. Let students know that their task will allow them to see how DNS solves the problem of having to keep track of IP addresses using GET requests to automatically retrieve these addresses. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 1 to use GET requests to obtain at least two classmates’ IP addresses and have a quick conversation.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Internet Simulator: DNS Queries",
        "progression_name": "Internet Simulator: DNS Queries"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a18ddc93-c0d3-4841-a1dd-35e2e4d285c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5a1ef943-475d-4c54-aa2d-294ba6787bb0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure that students are correctly sending GET requisitions and using retrieved IP addresses.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students shouldn’t need more than 5 minutes in order to gain insight into how DNS uses GET requests to solve the problem of keeping track of IP addresses and resolving human-readable usernames (or domain names) into IP addresses. Once you feel that your students have grasped this concept, you can move on the debrief and discuss DNS."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5a1ef943-475d-4c54-aa2d-294ba6787bb0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1951d0e2-835f-4764-bdd4-d3fa0ba01c2f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1951d0e2-835f-4764-bdd4-d3fa0ba01c2f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "df2c217b-6e54-4d9b-b1b7-fd346e515cef",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.\n- *What problem does DNS solve?*\n- *What did you notice about how GET requests work to retrieve information?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for answers that point out how DNS converts human-friendly usernames (or domain names) into machine-readable IP addresses and that GET requests structure how information is requested. DNS makes our lives easier by automatically handling the translation of names to IP addresses—just like a phone book.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video “The Internet: IP Addresses & DNS” from 4:10 to the end of the video. Have students focus on how DNS translates domain names and how the system scales.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "df2c217b-6e54-4d9b-b1b7-fd346e515cef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2637b46-72e3-4dba-a1f5-a892ad8890b8",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2637b46-72e3-4dba-a1f5-a892ad8890b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91c472bd-58da-4cb0-b201-65bbeea65b5a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the DNS Hierarchy handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that while the video gave a good summary of how DNS works, the reality of the process has many more layers! Their job is to quickly work with a DNS chatbot to fill in some missing information about the entire DNS Hierarchy and its process.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 2 to chat with the DNS Hierarchy chatbot to help them fill in the missing components in their handout.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "The DNS Hierarchy",
        "progression_name": "DNS Hierarchy Chatbot"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91c472bd-58da-4cb0-b201-65bbeea65b5a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c98ad804-457a-41cc-835b-126175a3e2b8",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure that students are using the suggested prompts to ask the chatbot for the missing information.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students shouldn’t need more than 5-8 minutes in order to interact with the chatbot to fill in their handout. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c98ad804-457a-41cc-835b-126175a3e2b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c63c973-9a40-4d67-829d-be016a22bbdd",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c63c973-9a40-4d67-829d-be016a22bbdd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2ed6529-e356-4d04-9d64-6c2928ad644a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.\n- *What problem does DNS solve?*\n- *What did you notice about how GET requests work to retrieve information?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for answers that point out how DNS converts human-friendly usernames (or domain names) into machine-readable IP addresses and that GET requests structure how information is requested. DNS makes our lives easier by automatically handling the translation of names to IP addresses—just like a phone book.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts:\n- *What do you notice about the DNS hierarchy?*\n- *What do you wonder about how it the hierarchy works?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Emphasize to students that this distributed hierarchy ensures scalability and efficiency, allowing DNS to handle billions of requests daily. Facilitate a discussion to clarify roles and highlight key points:\n- Recursive Resolver starts the process and queries other servers.\n- Root Servers guide the request to the correct TLD server.\n- TLD Servers handle requests for .com, .org, etc., and direct them to the Authoritative Server.\n- Authoritative Servers provide the IP address."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2ed6529-e356-4d04-9d64-6c2928ad644a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0e347c49-e5d3-462f-afb0-d303cc4aab8c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video segment of “The Internet: HTTP & HTML” Have students focus on how browsers retrieve content from servers and what GET and POST requests are.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the HTTP protocol to students.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 3 to complete Levels 3 through 5.\n- **Level 3:** Students access the HTTP Cats exploration external site.\n- **Level 4:** Students complete a check for understanding.\n- **Level 5:** Students complete a check for understanding.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "HTTP Preview and Inspect Tool Exploration",
        "progression_name": "HTTP Requests Exploration"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0e347c49-e5d3-462f-afb0-d303cc4aab8c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "12d0238d-bd52-4c03-b19e-0c8691894dff",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to user their Unit Guide to record observations about types of files that are being loaded and why it might be important for the browser to request only the files it needs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Move around the room to help students open the Inspect Tool, navigate to the Network tab, and identify different file types and status codes.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, ask students to share their observations with the class, including the types of files that were being loaded and why it is important for the browser to request only the files it needs. Draw out key takeaways such as DNS resolves the domain name into an IP address so HTTP knows where to send requests and how HTTP retrieves content in smaller pieces, ensuring efficiency and scalability."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Levels 4 and 5 can be used to formatively assess the learning objectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "12d0238d-bd52-4c03-b19e-0c8691894dff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46df5465-284b-438a-a58c-9b99194c830b",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46df5465-284b-438a-a58c-9b99194c830b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3a20eda-088b-4920-bf4c-4baf4368a5aa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a54f96be-5c71-4590-8c87-b6eed7e26b67",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a quick minute to jot down their thoughts on the Question of the Day. Encourage students to include at least one specific example from any of today’s activities.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to briefly share in one or two sentences how websites find their way to your browser using DNS and HTTP. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to small-group conversations and if time permits, call on two or three groups to share their key insights with the class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to build on each other’s ideas instead of just repeating the same answer. "
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- how DNS resolves domain names into IP addresses.\n- the function of HTTP in requesting web pages."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a54f96be-5c71-4590-8c87-b6eed7e26b67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5a5744e-96af-4b78-b7fd-71b4478f97fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "073c3fbc-98d3-4be2-8f9b-3b943c6461a3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "073c3fbc-98d3-4be2-8f9b-3b943c6461a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5a5744e-96af-4b78-b7fd-71b4478f97fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc7e5a79-0ff7-4482-bdd0-ccf60ac31636",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do websites use DNS and HTTP to load in your browser?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for answers that synthesize the process: DNS translates domain names into IP addresses, and HTTP uses GET requests to retrieve content from servers, working together to bring websites to life."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc7e5a79-0ff7-4482-bdd0-ccf60ac31636",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5a5744e-96af-4b78-b7fd-71b4478f97fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa7db066-f7a0-4494-9de1-e4a9b0ed86ef",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the Four Corners upcoming activity to students. Make sure to point out which corner will be **Yes**, **No**, **Maybe**, and **Undecided**.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the first scenario to students and direct them to move to the corner that best aligns whether they agree, disagree, think maybe or are unsure. Instruct students to discuss their reasoning with others who share their stance and then call on a student from each corner to share why their group chose their position.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage critical thinking about fairness, competition, and access on the Internet as well as cost barriers, freedom of information, or business interests."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa7db066-f7a0-4494-9de1-e4a9b0ed86ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32eae8c-6753-46f4-a5cd-bf534c99c846"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "357f67f5-f47a-4151-a52c-5e58d7ca4092",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "357f67f5-f47a-4151-a52c-5e58d7ca4092",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32eae8c-6753-46f4-a5cd-bf534c99c846"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "88584961-b4c0-4dbb-a3a6-95704807493b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the second scenario to students and direct them to move to the corner that best aligns whether they agree, disagree, think maybe or are unsure. Instruct students to discuss their reasoning with others who share their stance and then call on a student from each corner who was not a spokesperson for scenario #1 to share why their group chose their position.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the third scenario to students and direct them to move to the corner that best aligns whether they agree, disagree, think maybe or are unsure. Instruct students to discuss their reasoning with others who share their stance and then call on a student from each corner who was not a spokesperson for the previous two scenarios to share why their group chose their position.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce Net Neutrality to students and that all of the scenarios relate to net neutrality. Explain to students that this means that without net neutrality, Internet Service Providers (ISPs) can prioritize, slow down or even block websites and companies can pay for faster access creating advantages for some and barriers for others. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Net neutrality impacts who has access to fast, reliable Internet and who is left behind. If an ISP charges extra for faster speeds, who might struggle to afford it? How could this deepen the digital divide? Encourage students to think about these questions throughout the lesson. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "88584961-b4c0-4dbb-a3a6-95704807493b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32eae8c-6753-46f4-a5cd-bf534c99c846"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a6d5784-72cd-4712-823d-14fdf52c393d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a6d5784-72cd-4712-823d-14fdf52c393d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32eae8c-6753-46f4-a5cd-bf534c99c846"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5ec8639d-566b-41c3-9c8b-b743b208606d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ec8639d-566b-41c3-9c8b-b743b208606d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32eae8c-6753-46f4-a5cd-bf534c99c846"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "371cab51-0d7d-4e44-be5b-6817c47012fc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students in groups of two. Make sure students have their Unit Guides out and turned to Lesson 7 to record their observations in the next activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 5 to investigate the data from the Pew Research Center about Internet Access and discuss the questions with their partner.\n- **Level 1:** Students explore internet use over time.\n- **Level 2:** Students explore home broadband use by income.\n- **Level 3:** Students explore internet use by community type.\n- **Level 4:** Students explore internet use by age.\n- **Level 5:** Students explore smartphone dependency by education.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Digital Divide Data Analysis",
        "progression_name": "Pew Research Center: Internet Access"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "371cab51-0d7d-4e44-be5b-6817c47012fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab362d4b-903e-4dd3-b8c0-229a3ee4e077",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to record their observations in their Unit Guides as they discuss the questions on each level."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab362d4b-903e-4dd3-b8c0-229a3ee4e077",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ea92961c-e1e6-4798-89a5-4fb0d33e763d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we understand net neutrality, let’s explore the bigger picture: Who actually has access to the Internet? Together, we will look at the data from Pew Research and think about who benefits most and who gets left behind. I will put the graphs up on the board. You will also have a version of these graphs on your own computer so you can see them more clearly. ",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "In each level, students will have the opportunity to look at the interactive version of each graph by clicking on the link within each level. If time allows, encourage students to open the link in a new tab and use the “find” tool on their browser to quickly find the graph on the report page. Hovering over each data point will give them more information about the graph. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ea92961c-e1e6-4798-89a5-4fb0d33e763d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f52831b7-bb56-4e65-8f0c-c897a356bcf3",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f52831b7-bb56-4e65-8f0c-c897a356bcf3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e29a95c5-018b-4222-83f6-cbbf42ed8bec",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What do you notice about Internet access across different groups (e.g., income, geography, age)?*\n- *How might these disparities impact education, employment, or civic participation?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that Internet access is not distributed equally and that disparities exist based on income, geography, education, and age. Encourage students to connect these inequalities to opportunities in education, employment, and civic engagement, considering how limited access can reinforce existing societal divides. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the digital divide to students."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e29a95c5-018b-4222-83f6-cbbf42ed8bec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "713e946d-b188-4ac6-9089-4f90f2678a8e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Internet Access IRL activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 6 to choose one of the AI Chatbot personas that has been affected by the digital divide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Case Studies with AI Chatbot",
        "progression_name": "Choose a Persona"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "713e946d-b188-4ac6-9089-4f90f2678a8e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "74530f7f-5555-4638-9d69-e17032b1655d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for student discussions about access barriers (e.g., cost, availability, slow speeds). Prompt students to think whether the persona's experience compares to their own.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What did you learn about your persona?*\n- *How does this connect to the disparities we saw in the Pew Research data?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal of this discussion is to help students connect real-world technology access disparities to the personas they explored and the data from Pew Research. Students should recognize how limited access to the Internet affects different aspects of life, including education, jobs, healthcare, and civic participation. Finally, encourage them to think critically about possible solutions, including the role of policies like net neutrality in shaping digital equity."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "74530f7f-5555-4638-9d69-e17032b1655d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "06a0a0c3-2775-45f8-8240-20f30ab78f89",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "06a0a0c3-2775-45f8-8240-20f30ab78f89",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8076a8f8-8837-402a-a5d7-fe93158e7529"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce648c4c-33f2-4807-a8dd-810d66ca13a6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to write a short response to the Question of the Day and then have student pair up to share responses. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- the impact of the digital divide on different populations and potential solutions to address it.\n- Net neutrality and digital divide issues shape opportunities in education, jobs, and civic life."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce648c4c-33f2-4807-a8dd-810d66ca13a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0ebf68b1-bbe4-4ae0-8e8b-bbd4deae89a6"
      }
    },
